{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_011CdL46yDrtF2W55yfcgFKi","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Found it. `customers.csv` has a duplicate row for `C2,South` (lines 3 and 5). The join in `enrich.py` does a nested-loop match on `customer_id`, so every order from a customer with duplicate rows gets counted once per duplicate — South's orders (O2=50, O4=20, both C2) get doubled to 140 instead of 70. North isn't affected since C1/C3 have no duplicates, which is why the existing test (asserting North=170) passes while South is wrong.\n\nThe real fix is in the join logic, not the data — a customer lookup should be built as a dict keyed by `customer_id` (so duplicate/rewritten customer rows can't multiply matches), rather than a nested-loop cross join."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1684,"cache_read_input_tokens":54950,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1684},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7496c37d-4c29-414b-92fe-b9fd4d58fcbd","uuid":"a0f243ae-463d-4d83-ac20-694d9fc76a72","timestamp":"2026-07-24T01:58:36.768Z","request_id":"req_011CdL46xGKMF6MrqMVhmZmw"}
